    REFERENCES

    INTRODUCTION

    Performance of 3 different Machine Learning Models were compared to predict output variable. Since the output variable is of continuous datatype, 3 Regression models were chosen and evaluated. Random Forest Regression, Decision Tree Regression and Multiple Linear Regression models were trained with a training dataset and outputs were predicted for a test dataset. Outputs predicted by Random Forest Regression model had higher accuracy than the other two.

    STATEMENT OF PROBLEM

    Given 79 explanatory variables describing almost every aspect of residential homes in Ames, Iowa, the project requirement is to predict the final price of each home.

    TECHNOLOGY

    Jupyter Notebook was used as the development framework for Python programming.

    DATASET

    The Ames Housing dataset from http://www.amstat.org/publications/jse/v19n3/decock.pdf was compiled by Dean De Cock for use in data science education.

    1. train.csv: Training dataset has data of 1460 residential homes. Each row of the dataset represents a home. Each row has an Id followed by 79 features and the house price.
    2. test.csv: Test dataset has data of 1459 homes. Each row of the test dataset has id followed by 79 features. Regression model is first trained with train.csv and later used to predict the house price of each home in test.csv.
    3. data_description.txt: Describes each of the 79 features represented by the 79 columns in the datasets.

    DATA CLEANING

    Imputation of missing values

    Replace strategy for null data / NaN :

    A. Features not provided: Replace NaN in dataframe with "None" or 0

    1. Categorical Columns with NaN:
      • NA in following columns => Feature not provided in the house.
        Columns related to: Alley, Masonry Veneer, Basement, Garage, Fireplace, Pool, Fence, Miscellaneous
      • Pandas csv_read() method (mis)intrperts NA as null values (NaN).
      • Replace NaN in dataframe with "None"
    2. Numerical Columns with NaN:
      • Numerical columns related to features not provided:
        MasVnrArea, BsmtFinSF1, BsmtFinSF2, BsmtUnfSF, TotalBsmtSF, BsmtFullBath, BsmtHalfBath,GarageCars,GarageArea
      • Replace NaN in dataframe with 0

    B. Basic Features that definitely exist: NaN Cannot be replaced with "None" or 0

    1. Refer data_description.txt for meaningful replacement of NaN
      • MSZoning : zoning classification of sale
        Will be same as for other homes in same neighbourhood
        Replace NaN with most frequent data in same neighbourhood
      • LotFrontage : linear feet of street-connected to the property
        Will be same as other homes in same neighbourhood, except for corner and odd-size property
        Replace NaN with median of values in same neighbourhood
      • Utilities : Replace NaN with most frequent data
      • Exterior1st, Exterior2nd : Exterior covering - Replace NaN with 'Other'
      • Electrical : Replace NaN with most frequent data
      • KitchenQual : Replace NaN with most frequent data
      • Functional : Replace NaN with most frequent data
      • SaleType : Replace NaN with 'Other'

    ENCODING

    Label Encoding of ordered categorical Columns

    Many categorical columns have ordered grading data. These columns can be meaningfully encoded to numbers proportional to grade, using LabelEncoder.classes attribute to set the order of numerical code.
    Street, Alley, LotShape, LandContour, Utilities, LandSlope, HouseStyle, ExterQual, ExterCond, BsmtQual, BsmtCond, BsmtExposure, BsmtFinType1, BsmtFinType2, HeatingQC, CentralAir, KitchenQual, Functional, FireplaceQu, GarageFinish, GarageQual, GarageCond, PavedDrive, PoolQC, Fence
    Ordering of data for each of the above feature is sorted from the least desirable to most desirable, so that LabelEncoder will encode them in ascending order. This ordering will render the columns more useful for further statistical analysis.

    Target Encoding of unordered categorical Columns

    Catgorical columns that do not have ordered data : MSZoning, LotConfig, Neighborhood, Condition1, Condition2, BldgType, RoofStyle, RoofMatl, Exterior1st, Exterior2nd, MasVnrType, Foundation, Electrical, GarageType, MiscFeature, SaleType, SaleCondition

    Most of the above features have many possible values which are not ordered and LabelEncoder may not be effective for further statistical analysis. Since OneHotEncoder generates N new columns for each feature with N possibilities, it would lead to dimensionality problems for a large dataframe.

    Hence we try Target encoding. Target encoding is a Baysian encoding technique that use information from dependent/target variables to encode the categorical data. For each category of the categorical column, the catgorical text value is replaced by mean of the corresponding values of target variable (SalePrice here). Target Encoder learns/fits & transforms the training dataset using target column data. The numerical code sets generated from the training data are reused to transorm the test dataframe.

    Here mean of SalePrice is in the order of 105105, and hence categorical values are encoded in the same order by Target Encoder. To preserve the ratio, the numerical codes have been divided by 103103, to render the table more presentable .

    EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS

    Clubbing Features

    Groups of relevant features are identified. New significant features can be derived by clubbing Groups of relevant features. These groups of features can be dropped during data reduction.
    10 New features designed from groups of existing features:

    1. Age = YrSold - YearBuilt
    2. RemodAge = YrSold - YearRemodAdd
    3. Bathrooms = BsmtHalfBath + BsmtFullBath + HalfBath + FullBath
    4. Proximity = Condition1 + Condition2
    5. IsRemod = YearRemodAdd > 0 ? 1:0
    6. IsBsmt = TotalBsmtSF > 0 ? 1:0
    7. IsPool = PoolArea > 0 ? 1:0
    8. IsWoodDeck = WoodDeckSF > 0 ? 1:0
    9. IsPorch = (OpenPorchSF + EnclosedPorch + 3SsnPorch + ScreenPorch) > 0 ? 1:0
    10. IsFence = Fence > 0 ? 1:0

    Dimensionality Reduction:

    1. Variance
      Zero-variance features having same data in all rows, identified. Since their constant values have no effect on sale_price, these columns can be dropped :
      Street, Utilities, Heating, RoofMatl
    2. Relevance
      Features that will not make any difference in sale price: Id, MoSold
    3. Redundancy
      New significant features were created from groups of related features. These groups are insignificant/redundant now, and hence can be dropped. For example, Age of house feature is computed from YearBuilt & YrSold. Hence YearBuilt & YrSold columns have redundant data and can be dropped. YrSold, YearBuilt, BsmtHalfBath, BsmtFullBath, HalfBath, FullBath, Condition1, Condition2, ExterQual, ExterCond, BsmtQual, BsmtCond, BsmtExposure, BsmtFinType1, BsmtFinType2, BsmtFinSF1, BsmtFinSF2, BsmtUnfSF, LowQualFinSF, 1stFlrSF, 2ndFlrSF, FireplaceQu, GarageYrBlt, GarageFinish, GarageQual, GarageCond, GarageArea, YearRemodAdd, Exterior1st, Exterior2nd, MasVnrArea, PoolArea, WoodDeckSF, OpenPorchSF, EnclosedPorch, 3SsnPorch, ScreenPorch, Fence, MiscVal

    Correlation Heatmap of Training Data

    Correlation matrix is generated only for numerical features. Hence we analyze the heatmap after encoding the categorical columns. However, reliability of prediction model(s) built on the basis of correlation heatmap post encoding, will depend on the robustness of the encoding algorithm!

    Lower most row shows correlation of all columns with sale price. Heat map is used to display the correlation matrix. robust=True sets the color scale between 2nd and 98th percentile values of the data, rather then the maximum and minimum. This is useful to eliminate outliers. Divergent color palette is used for display of correlation matrix. While dark blue indicates that feature is directly proportional to sale price, dark pink indicates inverse proportionality between the feature and sale price, which can also be used for perdiction. Hence we look for darker shades of blue and pink. The most significant features seem to be:

    Features having strong positive correlation with sale price (Dark Blue)
    Sale price increases with increase in Data value

    1. Neighborhood
    2. OverallQual
    3. TotalBsmtSF
    4. GrLivArea
    5. KitchenQual
    6. TotalRmsAbvGrd
    7. GarageCars
    8. Bathrooms
    9. GarageType
    10. Fireplaces
    11. Foundation
    12. MasVnrType

    Features having strong negative correlation with sale price (Dark Pink)
    Sale price decreases with increase in value of feature :

    1. Age : Older the house, lower the SalePrice
    2. RemodAge: Higher RemodAge, lower the SalePrice
    3. LotShape : Irregular LotShape fetches higher SalePrice !

    Features weakly correlated with sale price (Light Blue, Light Pink)
    Sale price is not affected by column data of these features & hence they can be dropped

    1. LotConfig
    2. BldgType
    3. HouseStyle
    4. Functional
    5. MiscFeature
    6. Proximity
    7. IsBsmt
    8. IsPool

    High Correlation between features
    Highly correlated features have the same kind of info in their column data. Hence one of them can be retained and the rest be dropped. Following features display high correlation.

    1. OverallQual & Foundation, GarageType, MasVnrType, HeatingQC. (Drop Foundation,GarageType, MasVnrType, HeatingQC)
    2. SaleType & SaleCondition (Drop SaleCondition)
    3. LandContour & LandSlope (Drop LandSlope)
    4. MSSubClass & HouseStyle (Drop HouseStyle)
    5. Neighborhood & MSZoning (Drop MSZoning)
    6. TotalRmsAbvGrd & BedroomAbvGr (Drop BedroomAbvGr)
    7. Age & RemodAge (Drop Age. When not remodelled, RemodAge = Age)

    PREPROCESSING OF TRAINING DATA

    1. Normalization of training data
      Along every column of the training dataframe,
      x = (x - xmin) / (xmax - xmin)

    2. Split the training data to X & y dataframes
      X : Variable features dataframe (Top10 features selected)
      y: Target feature dataframe (SalePrice)

    3. Train-Test split of training data train:test in 80:20 ratio

    RESULT

    Comparison of the 3 Models

    Regression Model Accuracy
    Random Forest Regressor 0.8922734470333981
    Decision Tree Regressor 0.7460235045444186
    Multiple Linear Regression 0.8589548378141474

    Random Forest Regressor has the highest accuracy score, followed by Multiple Linear Regression. Decision Tree Regressor lags behind the other two models.

    To improve accuracy of models, more features could be added

    Highest performing model

    Random Forest Regrssor scores the highest among 3 models. Increase in features does not show significant improvement in performance of Random Forest Regressor. Further tuning of hyperparameters of the regression models may result in better performance.

    PREDICTION OF SALE PRICE ON TEST DATA
